[[~gopalv] doesn't inode id guarantee immutability? I remember discussing with someone that it would change on append., [~sershe]: this is true only for HDFS NameNodes (& appends don't change inode-ids - people who want to drive an HDFS developer insane can truncate an HDFS file to a smaller length and then append to it again to overwrite existing blocks).

FYI - https://www.ibm.com/support/knowledgecenter/STXKQY_5.0.0/com.ibm.spectrum.scale.v5r00.doc/bl1adv_Overviewhdfs.htm
, If that is also not a guaranteed on HDFS, should we just never use inode ID for updatable files like text? So, only ORC + HDFS would ever use inode ID. And then I think some ORC files are also theoretically appendable (isn't that how merge works?) so to be safe we can never use it, at least by default., The patch looks good to me... [~gopalv] any particular reason it's WIP?, [~sershe]: removed the extra config and defaults to synthetic file-ids if file-id paths are disabled., Heh, so it basically becomes an "is HDFS" config. +1, | (x) *{color:red}-1 overall{color}* |
